The Legendary Quartet:



Long before the sewers of Calimport echoed with the whispers of elemental malice, long before adventurers spoke in fearful tones about encounters with runaway genies, there existed a marvel of elemental diplomacy known as the Legendary Quartet. These four beings, each a powerful noble of their elemental kind, served roles that would shape the history of the Wizard Ward and leave a stain upon the sands of Calimshan. Their names were carved into both reverence and dread. They were a Marid of the boundless seas, an Efreeti forged in the heart of flame, a Djinn carried upon winds that danced above the dunes, and lastly a Dao whose body was carved from the very bones of the earth. Together, they formed an accord between the mortal scholars of the Wizard Ward and the primal powers of the Elemental Planes.



The Quartet was created through treaties older than many empires. Each genie bound itself willingly to the mages of the Ward in exchange for influence, knowledge, and access to a world they believed ripe for their philosophies to grow. Each believed the pact to be mutual. Each believed that under the watchful eyes of the arcane elite, their elemental essence would remain inviolate. Their service was to be a display of cooperation between the planes. Their power was to act as an endless font for the works of the Ward. Their presence was to make the Wizard Ward the most respected center of elemental research in all of Faern.



Yet mortals have always harbored a temptation that grows in the presence of power. The four genies were bound to a central covenant in the Hall of Transmutation, a place dedicated to reshaping matter, bending substance, and remaking reality. It was the pride of the Ward. Scholars from distant countries traveled to witness its marvels. Arcane engineers spoke poems of the golems crafted within its hallowed walls, constructs designed with beauty and purpose. They were the closest mortals had come to understanding creation.



It was in this hall that the first betrayal was seeded.



The mages had long sought to create a sentient construct, one capable of independent reasoning, creativity, and true will. They desired a golem that could learn and adapt without the restraints of simple commands. A construct that could serve as both guardian and scholar. Many methods were attempted. Rare crystals, enchanted hearts, runic matrices that glowed for only moments. Every attempt faltered. Every spark of intelligence flickered out before life could take hold.



That was when the idea formed, whispered first as a question, then fought as a debate, and eventually accepted by those who had grown accustomed to crossing lines in the name of progress. They would use genie essence to create sentience. Not merely energy drawn from a binding or a ritual, but the living core of an elemental noble. It was decided in private. It was hidden under the guise of research. It was justified through arguments of advancement and the greater good.

The genies knew nothing of the conspiracy. They continued to serve, believing their pact honored. Yet the Dao sensed something amiss. Unlike the others who thrived on freedom, motion, passion, and whims, the Dao was grounded in instinct, suspicion, and territorial pride. The Dao noticed the glances exchanged between apprentices. It heard the whispers that vanished when it walked near. It felt the subtle changes in the binding matrix that formed the foundation of their contract.

Earth remembers. Stone does not lie.



The Dao voiced its concerns to the others. The Efreeti laughed, dismissing it as paranoia. The Djinn brushed it aside, convinced that no mortal would dare break the pact under which they stood. The Marid encouraged caution but doubted treachery. In the end, the Dao stood alone in its suspicion, and that solitude sealed its fate.



When the moment came, the mages of the Hall invited the Quartet to participate in what they claimed was a ritual to strengthen their shared connection. It was said to deepen the bond between mortal and elemental power. The genies arrived with trust still unbroken. Before the ritual began, the Dao paused. Its instincts screamed. Something was wrong. It attempted to leave, but the mages unleashed prepared wards that sealed the chamber and stole control of its movements. The Dao surged with power, shaking the stones themselves, but it was too late. The others watched in horror as the ritual circle flared and the Dao was pulled apart from within.



The scream of an earth genie is unlike any mortal death cry. It is the agony of collapsing caverns, the roar of landslides, the shattering of mountains. The Hall of Transmutation shook under the weight of its demise. The mages pressed on in cold determination. They harvested the swirling fragments of the Dao's essence and infused them into their newest golems. These constructs awakened. They were not mere machines. They possessed something that resembled will. Something that resembled soul. Something that resembled hunger.



They were alive, and they were watchers, and they were weapons.



The remaining three genies broke their bindings in an act of elemental fury. The Efreeti burst forth in a wave of heat that melted runes and scorched apprentices. The Marid's waters surged, drowning out spellwork and sweeping mages aside. The Djinn vanished from sight with the silence of an approaching storm. The three fled the Ward, leaving chaos in their wake, but not without taking with them a wound that time could not heal. Betrayal had ended their trust in mortals. Grief had shattered their unity. Rage had given them new purpose.



They were no longer the guardians of the Wizard Ward. They had become something else entirely. They had become rogues.

Their escape into the undercity was no accident. They sought a place untouched by the scripts and sigils of the Ward. A place where their enemies could not redraw the chains that once bound them. Beneath Calimport lay miles of tunnels, ancient channels, forgotten passages, broken waterworks, and networks of caverns worn through stone and sand. It was here that the three found refuge. It was here that they discovered freedom once more.



Yet freedom did not ease their wounds. The loss of the Dao haunted them. The Efreeti's rage grew hotter, fueled by the memory of stone torn to dust. The Marid's sorrow deepened, transforming once gentle waters into crushing tides of resentment. The Djinn withdrew into cold indifference that masked a wounded heart. The trio had been united once by trust. Now they were united by vengeance.



In the sewers, their presence twisted the environment around them. The Efreeti's heat caused pockets of superheated air, forming steam vents and melted stone tunnels. The Marid's magic strengthened the flow of subterranean rivers, making pools deeper and currents unpredictable. The Djinn's storms stirred drafts in empty corridors and animated dust devils in abandoned halls.



Over time, they came to be spoken of in fearful whispers. Sewer dwellers called them the Rogue Genies. Adventurers who survived encounters with them dubbed them the Legendary Quartet in remembrance of the Dao who was taken. Rumors spread that the trio sought revenge not only against the Ward but against anyone who aligned themselves with arcane authority. Some claimed they sought to free other bound elementals. Others believed they plotted the destruction of the Hall of Transmutation itself. A few whispered that they sought ways to reclaim the Dao's stolen essence and restore their fallen companion, no matter the cost.

Despite their withdrawal, they remained bound to each other by guilt. Each blamed themselves for ignoring the Dao's warnings. Each swore to avenge the betrayal. Each carried a fragment of the Dao's memory that strengthened their resolve.



What they did not know was that the constructs in the Hall of Transmutation continued to grow in power. The sentient golems infused with the Dao's essence whispered among themselves. Some claimed to feel echoes of the earth genie's spirit. Others claimed that the Dao was not entirely dead. Its essence, though torn and scattered, might be whole enough to call out to the surviving three.



In this way the tale of the Legendary Quartet is unfinished. They dwell in the sewers with growing malice and sorrow, but their story has not reached its end. Whether they will rise in wrath to challenge the Ward, whether they will seek to reclaim the Dao's stolen soul, or whether their grief will transform them into something far worse remains unknown. Yet the people of Calimport whisper of tremors beneath the Wizard Ward, of winds turning colder in the alleys, of water shifting strangely in the canals, and of heat radiating through the stone even in the cool hours of dawn.



Some say it is a warning.

Some say it is a promise.

Some say the Legendary Quartet will rise again.
